text:
90% of today's issues with climate change can be solved using science that is already well known. Space travel and GMO are the single quickest ways to reduce our emissions. Space travel removes two of the biggest burdens on our planet: overpopulation and the exponentially increasing need for more resources. Space is both unlimited in size and in resources. Mining a single astroid could provide more raw material than has been mined in the past century. Rotating habitats in space are not simply science fiction. This form of artificial habitat is something easily achievable with today's technology. And with space being a vaccum, any pollution released would simply dissipate into the void, no harm done.

 GMOs are another great example. I see a lot of people in the comments below asking for people to stop supporting the agricultural industry. This is ABSOLUTELY true. The single greatest force responsible for the destruction of natural habitats is the agricultural industry. More than 50% of the habitable space on earth is taken up simply for the task of producing food. But here's the thing. These same people I see arguing against this industry also argue against GMO. Here's a simple fact: organic agriculture will NEVER support a population over 5 billion. It is actually impossible. This is why GMOs are essential. GMOs have the benefit of being engineered to thrive in much different conditions than their "natural" cousins. We can make stacked hydroponic farms that provide just as much food while taking up thousands of times less space. And for the people who hate the meat industry. That too can be modified. As much as no one wants to hear it, growing meat is the most ethical and efficient way to get it. If you grow a chunk of meat in a tube it is completely under your control. It will never feel and never think, so eating it is completely without ethical complication. Eating tube grown meat is no more wrong than eating a potatoe. This meat will also consume far less resources and release far less pollution than its animal counterpart. We could feed hundreds of billions of people in a way that is far more ethical and efficient than anything we have today. These changes must be made in order for humans to continue to thrive!
